Maureen Ihua-Maduenyi The Lagos Waste Management Authority has said it will support Edo State Government in its efforts to build a robust waste management system. The Managing Director of LAWMA, Dr Muyiwa Gbadegesin, said this when the management team of Edo State Waste Management Board visited him on a three-day fact- finding mission. Gbadegesin said the partnership between LAWMA and its Edo State counterpart would encourage sharing of ideas for improved waste management in both states. He stated that effective waste management and sustainable sanitation culture could be a long journey that would necessitate continuous introduction of innovative ideas to tackle the day-to-day challenges of managing backlogs of refuse generated in the metropolis. The Chief Operating Officer of LAWMA, Mr Ibrahim Odumboni, enlightened the guests from Edo State on the private sector participants’ scheme, their mode of operation, and the delineation of wards for billing and effective waste collection across the state. LAWMA’s Assistant Director, Business Development and Strategy, Dr Essien Nsuabia, also spoke on the evolution of LAWMA in waste management in the state and the various initiatives introduced by the agency to establish cleaner and livable environment. The General Manager of Edo State Waste Management Board, Mr Charles Imariagbe, said the visit provided them the opportunity of learning the strategies adopted by LAWMA in meeting the waste management needs of residents of Lagos State. The team, in the course of the visit, embarked on a tour of some of the LAWMA’s facilities such as Simpson and Oshodi Transfer Loading Stations and Olusosun dumpsite for first-hand assessment. Copyright PUNCH.
